1
00:00:01,959 --> 00:00:06,417
PICARD:
<i>Captain's log,</i>
<i>Stardate 42625.4.</i>

2
00:00:06,458 --> 00:00:08,750
<i>We are entering orbit</i>
<i>around the eighth planet</i>

3
00:00:08,792 --> 00:00:13,083
<i>in this previously unmapped</i>
<i>Theta 116 solar system.</i>

4
00:00:13,125 --> 00:00:15,291
<i>We diverted from our</i>
<i>scheduled course</i>

5
00:00:15,333 --> 00:00:17,208
<i>when a passing Klingon cruiser</i>

6
00:00:17,250 --> 00:00:20,083
<i>reported discovering</i>
<i>pieces of a strange vessel</i>

7
00:00:20,125 --> 00:00:23,041
<i>in the upper atmosphere</i>
<i>of this planet.</i>

8
00:00:23,083 --> 00:00:25,166
<i>We have come to investigate.</i>

9
00:00:25,208 --> 00:00:26,625
Nasty.

10
00:00:26,667 --> 00:00:30,083
Nitrogen, methane,
liquid neon.

11
00:00:30,125 --> 00:00:33,917
Surface temperature,
-291 degrees Celsius.

12
00:00:33,959 --> 00:00:38,208
Winds up to 312 meters
per second.

13
00:00:38,250 --> 00:00:40,625
Not exactly a
vacation planet, huh?

14
00:00:40,667 --> 00:00:44,417
Mm-mm, not unless you
like ammonia tornados.

15
00:00:44,458 --> 00:00:46,250
But I have found
indications of debris

16
00:00:46,291 --> 00:00:47,959
in an elliptical orbit.

17
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:49,625
RIKER:
You keep me informed.

18
00:00:49,667 --> 00:00:51,875
The sooner we find out what
the Klingons think they saw,

19
00:00:51,917 --> 00:00:53,583
the sooner we can get
the hell out of here.

20
00:00:53,625 --> 00:00:55,583
Sounds good to me.

21
00:00:58,792 --> 00:01:01,417
(<i> shivers</i> )
Nasty.

22
00:01:01,458 --> 00:01:02,834
(<i> door chimes</i> )

23
00:01:02,875 --> 00:01:04,500
Come.

24
00:01:08,959 --> 00:01:10,291
Fermat's last theorem.

25
00:01:10,333 --> 00:01:11,959
You're familiar
with it?

26
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:13,333
Vaguely.

27
00:01:13,375 --> 00:01:14,750
I spent too many
math classes

28
00:01:14,792 --> 00:01:16,542
daydreaming about
being on a starship.

29
00:01:16,583 --> 00:01:18,083
Mmm.

30
00:01:18,125 --> 00:01:21,000
When Pierre de Fermat died,
they found this equation

31
00:01:21,041 --> 00:01:23,250
scrawled in the margin
of his notes--

32
00:01:23,291 --> 00:01:26,125
"X to the nth plus Y to
the nth equals Z to the nth

33
00:01:26,166 --> 00:01:27,667
where N is greater
than two,"

34
00:01:27,709 --> 00:01:30,083
which he said had no
solution in whole numbers.

35
00:01:30,125 --> 00:01:35,500
But, he also added this
phrase, "remarkable proof."

36
00:01:35,542 --> 00:01:37,000
Yeah, that's starting
to come back to me.

37
00:01:37,041 --> 00:01:38,458
There was no proof included.

38
00:01:38,500 --> 00:01:40,792
Mm-hmm, and for
800 years,

39
00:01:40,834 --> 00:01:42,500
people have been
trying to solve it.

40
00:01:42,542 --> 00:01:43,792
Including you.

41
00:01:43,834 --> 00:01:45,417
I find it stimulating.

42
00:01:45,458 --> 00:01:48,291
Also, it puts things
in perspective.

43
00:01:48,333 --> 00:01:51,959
In our arrogance,
we feel we are so advanced.

44
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
And yet, we cannot
unravel a simple knot

45
00:01:55,041 --> 00:01:57,834
tied by a part-time
French mathematician

46
00:01:57,875 --> 00:02:02,041
working alone
without a computer.

47
00:02:02,083 --> 00:02:05,250
Captain, we've detected some
sort of debris in loose orbit.

48
00:02:05,291 --> 00:02:07,000
Can you identify it?
No, sir.

49
00:02:07,041 --> 00:02:09,417
I suggest we beam a section
aboard for analysis.

50
00:02:09,458 --> 00:02:11,458
Make it so, Number One.

51
00:02:21,875 --> 00:02:24,041
We've locked onto something
with markings on it.

52
00:02:24,083 --> 00:02:25,041
What sort
of markings?

53
00:02:25,083 --> 00:02:27,959
Uncertain.
Energize.

54
00:02:52,375 --> 00:02:55,125
We've got ourselves
a little puzzle, Number One.

55
00:02:55,166 --> 00:02:57,542
Yes, sir,
I guess we have.

56
00:03:24,125 --> 00:03:28,750
PICARD:
<i>Space, the final frontier.</i>

57
00:03:28,792 --> 00:03:32,792
<i>These are the voyages</i>
<i>of the Starship</i> Enterprise.

58
00:03:32,834 --> 00:03:34,542
<i>Its continuing mission--</i>

59
00:03:34,583 --> 00:03:38,709
<i>to explore</i>
<i>strange new worlds,</i>

60
00:03:38,750 --> 00:03:43,208
<i>to seek out new life</i>
<i>and new civilizations,</i>

61
00:03:43,250 --> 00:03:47,458
<i>to boldly go</i>
<i>where no one has gone before.</i>

62
00:04:47,583 --> 00:04:49,125
Analysis bears out
that the object

63
00:04:49,166 --> 00:04:51,917
was definitely
terrestrial in origin

64
00:04:51,959 --> 00:04:53,667
dated mid-21st century.

65
00:04:53,709 --> 00:04:56,208
No, no.
No Earth ship of that time

66
00:04:56,250 --> 00:04:58,291
could have traveled
out this far.

67
00:04:58,333 --> 00:05:00,709
Nevertheless, that is
what our tests indicate.

68
00:05:00,750 --> 00:05:02,750
And the markings we
discovered are consistent

69
00:05:02,792 --> 00:05:04,250
with this hypothesis.

70
00:05:04,291 --> 00:05:07,000
Any indication
of what destroyed it, Data?

71
00:05:07,041 --> 00:05:08,834
That is even
more significant

72
00:05:08,875 --> 00:05:10,750
than the object itself,
Counselor.

73
00:05:10,792 --> 00:05:12,291
On several of
its surfaces,

74
00:05:12,333 --> 00:05:14,333
the molecules seem to
have disintegrated.

75
00:05:14,375 --> 00:05:16,375
Disintegrated how?

76
00:05:16,417 --> 00:05:20,458
Almost as if they were hit
by a weapon from our time.

77
00:05:20,500 --> 00:05:23,375
Curiouser
and curiouser.

78
00:05:23,417 --> 00:05:25,000
WESLEY:
Captain, we've detected

79
00:05:25,041 --> 00:05:27,417
a large structure
on the planet.

80
00:05:30,625 --> 00:05:32,750
WESLEY:
It's a building of some sort,

81
00:05:32,792 --> 00:05:35,417
situated on a plane
of frozen methane

82
00:05:35,458 --> 00:05:38,333
smack in the middle of a
tremendous storm belt.

83
00:05:38,375 --> 00:05:39,750
I don't believe this.

84
00:05:39,792 --> 00:05:41,709
That structure is surrounded
with breathable air.

85
00:05:41,750 --> 00:05:43,667
Is there any connection
between that structure

86
00:05:43,709 --> 00:05:45,291
and the ship fragment
that we found?

87
00:05:45,333 --> 00:05:47,750
Unknown, sir.

88
00:05:47,792 --> 00:05:49,417
Suggestions?

89
00:05:49,458 --> 00:05:52,041
Well just one, sir-- we can go
down there and have a look.

90
00:05:52,083 --> 00:05:53,375
Breathable air.

91
00:05:53,417 --> 00:05:55,500
No life forms that
might be dangerous.

92
00:05:55,542 --> 00:05:57,000
I think we could risk

93
00:05:57,041 --> 00:05:59,125
a minimal away team,
Number One.

94
00:06:00,834 --> 00:06:02,375
Give me a moment, gents,
we're dealing with

95
00:06:02,417 --> 00:06:04,792
an extremely
narrow access point.

96
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,083
Phasers on stun.

97
00:06:11,125 --> 00:06:13,417
Ready when you are.

98
00:06:13,458 --> 00:06:15,291
I believe we've got it now.

99
00:06:15,333 --> 00:06:16,875
You have a green light,
Commander.

100
00:06:16,917 --> 00:06:18,166
Energize.

101
00:06:35,917 --> 00:06:38,542
Those ammonia storms are less
than a kilometer away.

102
00:06:38,583 --> 00:06:42,000
Yet they do not appear to
penetrate this breathable zone.

103
00:06:42,041 --> 00:06:43,667
It's like the eye
of a hurricane.

104
00:06:43,709 --> 00:06:47,291
Commander, what is that?

105
00:06:55,709 --> 00:06:57,583
A door.

106
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:04,291
The structure must be here,
yet we cannot see it.

107
00:07:06,917 --> 00:07:09,667
Enterprise,
this is Commander Riker.

108
00:07:09,709 --> 00:07:12,917
As your readout shows,
this is an unusual place.

109
00:07:12,959 --> 00:07:16,750
Completely calm, no sound,
no movement,

110
00:07:16,792 --> 00:07:20,166
yet a few hundred meters away,
a storm is raging.

111
00:07:20,208 --> 00:07:22,291
PICARD: Any information
about the structure?

112
00:07:22,333 --> 00:07:24,875
Yes, sir, there's an
antique revolving door.

113
00:07:24,917 --> 00:07:26,166
It could be an entrance.

114
00:07:27,166 --> 00:07:29,542
Revolving door?

115
00:07:29,583 --> 00:07:31,792
Number One,
proceed with caution.

116
00:07:31,834 --> 00:07:34,625
RIKER:
Yes, sir.

117
00:07:34,667 --> 00:07:37,333
Well, this is what
we came here for.

118
00:07:37,375 --> 00:07:38,875
Captain, we're entering.

119
00:07:48,792 --> 00:07:52,792
(<i> conversational chatter</i>
<i>and slot machines ringing</i> )

120
00:08:19,125 --> 00:08:22,041
<i>Enterprise</i> to away team,
come in.

121
00:08:22,083 --> 00:08:25,166
We're receiving no signal
at all from them, sir.

122
00:08:26,542 --> 00:08:28,333
Transporter room,
lock on to the landing party,

123
00:08:28,375 --> 00:08:30,125
beam them up.

124
00:08:30,166 --> 00:08:32,709
We've got nothing
to lock on to, sir.

125
00:08:33,667 --> 00:08:35,166
Riker to<i> Enterprise.</i>

126
00:08:35,208 --> 00:08:37,166
We've entered
the structure.

127
00:08:38,458 --> 00:08:40,959
Riker to<i> Enterprise,</i> 
come in.

128
00:08:42,667 --> 00:08:44,542
Come in,<i> Enterprise.</i>

129
00:08:45,875 --> 00:08:47,834
When they went through
that antique doorway,

130
00:08:47,875 --> 00:08:49,792
their signal just
disappeared, sir.

131
00:08:51,667 --> 00:08:54,333
What's causing
the interference?

132
00:08:54,375 --> 00:08:55,542
Unknown.

133
00:08:55,583 --> 00:08:58,000
They're receiving us?

134
00:08:58,041 --> 00:08:59,583
No.

135
00:08:59,625 --> 00:09:01,375
We're going to have to
recalibrate all the frequencies

136
00:09:01,417 --> 00:09:02,959
to find one that'll work.

137
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:04,875
Then do it.

138
00:09:10,792 --> 00:09:15,000
Sir, without communication,
we should beam up immediately.

139
00:09:15,041 --> 00:09:17,333
We're here.
There's no danger.

140
00:09:17,375 --> 00:09:19,250
We'll look around,
then leave.

141
00:09:19,291 --> 00:09:20,458
Checking in, gentlemen?

142
00:09:20,500 --> 00:09:22,792
You'll have to go
to the front desk.

143
00:09:22,834 --> 00:09:25,583
Very good.
We'll start with that.

144
00:09:38,083 --> 00:09:39,500
(<i> clears throat</i> )

145
00:09:41,333 --> 00:09:43,000
Welcome, gentlemen.

146
00:09:44,583 --> 00:09:46,500
Have a nice trip?

147
00:09:49,667 --> 00:09:51,500
Do you know us?

148
00:09:51,542 --> 00:09:53,291
We've been expecting you.

149
00:09:53,333 --> 00:09:56,417
A trio of
foreign gentlemen.

150
00:09:56,458 --> 00:09:59,250
Yes, we're from the United
Federation of Planets.

151
00:09:59,291 --> 00:10:01,583
Of course you are.

152
00:10:01,625 --> 00:10:03,709
Welcome to the Hotel Royale.

153
00:10:07,208 --> 00:10:09,917
Excuse me.
Did Rita call?

154
00:10:09,959 --> 00:10:11,291
I'm busy.

155
00:10:11,333 --> 00:10:12,667
You're busy?

156
00:10:12,709 --> 00:10:14,792
This is my life
I'm talking about here.

157
00:10:14,834 --> 00:10:18,375
Now, did Rita call
or not?

158
00:10:18,417 --> 00:10:20,709
No, and for your own good,

159
00:10:20,750 --> 00:10:22,959
you better quit
thinking about Rita.

160
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:24,625
I'm not afraid
of Mickey D.

161
00:10:24,667 --> 00:10:26,041
Then you're a fool.

162
00:10:26,083 --> 00:10:29,125
Anybody with any sense
is afraid of Mickey D.

163
00:10:29,166 --> 00:10:32,041
If Rita calls,
you let me know.

164
00:10:41,333 --> 00:10:43,291
Kid's just asking
for trouble.

165
00:10:43,333 --> 00:10:44,959
Rita's too much
for him to handle,

166
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:47,917
and Mickey D's gonna plant
his face in the pavement.

167
00:10:49,542 --> 00:10:52,542
Now, here are your room keys.

168
00:10:58,709 --> 00:11:01,834
And some complimentary
casino chips.

169
00:11:09,959 --> 00:11:12,041
Enjoy.

170
00:11:14,166 --> 00:11:15,875
What is this place?

171
00:11:15,917 --> 00:11:18,500
How did a being
like you get here?

172
00:11:18,542 --> 00:11:20,792
Well, this is the Royale,
of course.

173
00:11:20,834 --> 00:11:22,166
And my personal life is really

174
00:11:22,208 --> 00:11:23,750
none of your business,
thank you.

175
00:11:23,792 --> 00:11:26,917
What he means is
what planet is this?

176
00:11:26,959 --> 00:11:28,208
I beg your pardon?

177
00:11:28,250 --> 00:11:31,250
This planet--
what do you call it?

178
00:11:31,291 --> 00:11:32,750
Earth.

179
00:11:32,792 --> 00:11:34,667
What do you call it?

180
00:11:34,709 --> 00:11:36,917
We call it Theta Eight.

181
00:11:37,875 --> 00:11:39,667
How charming.

182
00:12:03,583 --> 00:12:04,667
Commander?

183
00:12:04,709 --> 00:12:06,083
Yes, Data?

184
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:10,875
None of these people
are emitting life signs.

185
00:12:10,917 --> 00:12:14,291
You mean,
they're not alive?

186
00:12:14,333 --> 00:12:16,500
Then what are they?

187
00:12:16,542 --> 00:12:20,625
(<i> overlapping chatter</i> )

188
00:12:28,250 --> 00:12:31,834
These beings--
are they machines,

189
00:12:31,875 --> 00:12:35,041
or mere illusions
designed to deceive us?

190
00:12:35,083 --> 00:12:38,208
Not illusion, Lieutenant.
They do exist.

191
00:12:38,250 --> 00:12:41,291
But they do not register
as either man or machine.

192
00:12:43,166 --> 00:12:45,959
Take this creature,
for example.

193
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:49,834
He does not exhibit
any DNA structure.

194
00:12:49,875 --> 00:12:51,625
Excuse me, son.

195
00:12:51,667 --> 00:12:53,208
Look who's talking.

196
00:12:53,250 --> 00:12:56,250
Man, you sound just like
my ex-wife.

197
00:12:57,875 --> 00:12:59,417
All right.

198
00:12:59,458 --> 00:13:03,291
Time to get down
to "bidness."

199
00:13:03,333 --> 00:13:04,625
What sort of "bidness"

200
00:13:04,667 --> 00:13:07,000
do you suppose he is
getting down to?

201
00:13:17,917 --> 00:13:19,417
Status report.

202
00:13:19,458 --> 00:13:22,291
We're attempting to employ
alternate encoding schemes.

203
00:13:22,333 --> 00:13:25,291
There could be hundreds
of possible combinations.

204
00:13:27,375 --> 00:13:30,500
Is there an intelligence
causing this interference?

205
00:13:30,542 --> 00:13:31,834
Mmm.

206
00:13:31,875 --> 00:13:34,709
No, that's impossible
to tell, Captain.

207
00:13:46,834 --> 00:13:51,709
It's unlike Commander Riker
not to follow procedure.

208
00:13:51,750 --> 00:13:53,417
When he lost contact
with the<i> Enterprise</i>

209
00:13:53,458 --> 00:13:54,834
he should have
returned immediately

210
00:13:54,875 --> 00:13:56,917
to the beam-down
coordinates.

211
00:13:56,959 --> 00:13:59,959
I don't feel he's
in any danger.

212
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:03,500
In fact, if I could choose
one word to assess his mood,

213
00:14:03,542 --> 00:14:05,583
it would be amused.

214
00:14:07,417 --> 00:14:09,291
"Amused?"

215
00:14:10,667 --> 00:14:12,417
(<i> sighs</i> )

216
00:14:15,250 --> 00:14:16,709
What about some chips there,
mister?

217
00:14:16,750 --> 00:14:18,709
Yessiree!
(<i> laughing</i> )

218
00:14:18,750 --> 00:14:20,667
Oh.

219
00:14:20,709 --> 00:14:22,083
You're new around
here, aren't you?

220
00:14:22,125 --> 00:14:23,709
Yes, sir.
Then sit down.

221
00:14:23,750 --> 00:14:26,208
I'm gonna teach you how
this game is played, boy.

222
00:14:26,250 --> 00:14:29,250
(<i> laughing</i> )

223
00:14:29,291 --> 00:14:30,625
Go ahead, ante up.

224
00:14:30,667 --> 00:14:33,083
(<i> inhales deeply</i> )
I'll be.

225
00:14:34,917 --> 00:14:36,834
He wants you
to cut the cards.

226
00:14:36,875 --> 00:14:38,750
Ah!
Is this poker?

227
00:14:38,792 --> 00:14:40,166
No, no. Blackjack.

228
00:14:41,291 --> 00:14:42,709
Blackjack.

229
00:14:42,750 --> 00:14:44,250
Accessing.

230
00:14:45,917 --> 00:14:48,542
Ah, also known as "21."

231
00:14:48,583 --> 00:14:50,875
A number which defines
the object of the game.

232
00:14:50,917 --> 00:14:53,000
Picture cards
are worth ten,

233
00:14:53,041 --> 00:14:54,667
aces, one or 11,

234
00:14:54,709 --> 00:14:57,333
all other cards,
face value.

235
00:14:57,375 --> 00:14:59,041
Boy, you're right.

236
00:14:59,083 --> 00:15:00,750
You are right.

237
00:15:03,792 --> 00:15:05,458
(<i> whistles</i> )

238
00:15:05,500 --> 00:15:06,875
MAN:
Pretty smooth.

239
00:15:06,917 --> 00:15:08,792
Run 'em, boy.

240
00:15:08,834 --> 00:15:11,083
Make 'em nice, 'cause ain't
no bread in the house.

241
00:15:16,500 --> 00:15:17,583
21, 21, 21.

242
00:15:17,625 --> 00:15:19,834
Don't look at
your hand, honey.

243
00:15:19,875 --> 00:15:23,291
That gal has got to win.

244
00:15:23,333 --> 00:15:27,041
Now, honey, you got 15 and
the dealer's showing ten.

245
00:15:28,625 --> 00:15:30,500
Do I hit, Texas,
or do I stand?

246
00:15:30,542 --> 00:15:33,417
If you gotta win,
you gotta hit.

247
00:15:34,583 --> 00:15:35,792
Hit me.

248
00:15:37,250 --> 00:15:38,250
Ooh.

249
00:15:38,291 --> 00:15:39,834
TEXAS: Aw.
Damn!

250
00:15:39,875 --> 00:15:41,542
Shoot.

251
00:15:41,583 --> 00:15:42,625
Hit me.

252
00:15:44,792 --> 00:15:48,375
Twenty-one, and a winner.
Yessiree!

253
00:15:48,417 --> 00:15:50,000
Hit me.

254
00:15:51,750 --> 00:15:53,000
Another, please.

255
00:15:53,041 --> 00:15:55,542
Don't you think
you've had about enough?

256
